SIMPLE: titmouse
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Titmouse
<hw>Tit"mouse`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Titmice</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>titemose</ets>,
<ets>titmase</ets>; <ets>tit</ets> small, or a small bird + AS.
<ets>m⟦amac⟧se</ets> a kind of small bird; akin to D. <ets>mees</ets> a
titmouse, G. <ets>meise</ets>, OHG. <ets>meisa</ets>, Icel.
<ets>meisingr</ets>. The English form has been influenced by the
unrelated word <ets>mouse</ets>. Cf. <er>Tit</er> a small bird.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of small
insectivorous singing birds belonging to <gen>Parus</gen> and allied
genera; -- called also <altname>tit</altname>, and
<altname>tomtit</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The blue titmouse (<spn>Parus coeruleus</spn>), the
marsh titmouse (<spn>Parus palustris</spn>), the crested titmouse
(<spn>Parus cristatus</spn>), the great titmouse (<spn>Parus
major</spn>), and the long tailed titmouse (<spn>Aegithalos
caudatus</spn>), are the best-known European species. See
<er>Chickadee</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Titrate</ent>⟦br⟧
